---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Sidebar from '../components/Sidebar.astro';
import ImprintOverlay from '../components/ImprintOverlay.astro';
import IntroCarouselOverlay from '../components/IntroCarouselOverlay.astro';
import IntroVideo from '../components/sections/IntroVideo.astro';
import WorkSection from '../components/sections/WorkSection.astro';
import Releases from '../components/sections/Releases.astro';
import About from '../components/sections/About.astro';
import Dates from '../components/sections/Dates.astro';
import ParticleSection from '../components/sections/ParticleSection.astro';
---

<Layout>
  <Sidebar />
  <ImprintOverlay />
  <IntroCarouselOverlay />

  <main class="content">

    <IntroVideo />

    <WorkSection
      id="work-1"
      year="2026"
      title="Schimmelreiter"
      type="Music for Film"
      background="video"
      videoId="video-1"
      videoHls="https://vz-64816067-a45.b-cdn.net/6bd60ee1-68c9-4533-9e74-df29674c7a00/playlist.m3u8"
      previewClass="section-preview"
      previewId="preview-schi"
      previewImage="./pictures/Schimmelreiter_Perform.webp"
      playerBodyId="bp-1"
      playerType="video"
      playerDataVideo="video-1"
      playerLabel="PLAY VIDEO"
    >
      <Fragment slot="body">
        This project approaches film as an experiment from a musical perspective. Inspired by Theodor Storm's Der Schimmelreiter, it develops a fragmented, drifting narrative rather than directly adapting the original work. Images, subtitles, and a live ambient score are presented simultaneously, allowing narrative elements and atmosphere to emerge without fixed structure. Supported by the Verband für aktuelle Musik Hamburg we were able to shoot and direct the movie ourselfs within a few days and show the work in a Cinema in Hamburg.
        <span class="intro-arrow" id="arrow-schi"><b>→</b></span>
        <span class="credits">Photo: Thắng Lê-Phước</span>
      </Fragment>
    </WorkSection>

    <WorkSection
      id="work-2"
      year="2025"
      title="Longing"
      type="Audiovisual Performance"
      background="video"
      videoId="video-2"
      videoHls="https://vz-64816067-a45.b-cdn.net/7b83cc48-31c9-4cb9-8315-0733407a57ba/playlist.m3u8"
      previewClass="dot-preview"
      previewId="preview-longing"
      previewImage="./pictures/Longing(1).webp"
      playerBodyId="bp-2"
      playerType="video"
      playerDataVideo="video-2"
      playerLabel="PLAY VIDEO"
    >
      <Fragment slot="body">
        The series of audiovisual performances titled "Longing" is based on Joseph von Eichendorff's poem "Die blaue Blume" and explores the Romantic theme of longing. The project investigates this emotional dimension through the use of various field recording methods, particularly in urban environments. Walks, conversations, and reflections on personal impressions give rise to multi-layered soundscapes, which are presented as live arrangements in conjunction with filmed observations inspired by Slow Cinema. The project has already been realized in Bratislava, Stockholm, and Hamburg and is conceived as a transdisciplinary approach that combines sound, image, and personal experiences to facilitate an immersive engagement with the theme of longing.
        <span class="intro-arrow" id="view-longing"><b>→</b></span>
        <br>
        <span class="credits">Poster Design: David Kulev</span>
      </Fragment>
    </WorkSection>

    <WorkSection
      id="work-3"
      year="2024"
      title="Study for Pipe Organ"
      type="Site-Specific Concert"
      background="carousel"
      carouselImages={['./pictures/Pipe-Organ_1.webp', './pictures/Pipe-Organ_2.webp', './pictures/Pipe-Organ_3.webp']}
      previewClass="dot-preview-right"
      previewId="preview-organ"
      previewImage="./pictures/ListeningSess_Plakat.webp"
      playerBodyId="bp-3"
      playerType="audio"
      audioSrc="./pictures/kirche_schnelsen_demo1.mp3"
      playerLabel="PLAY AUDIO"
    >
      <Fragment slot="body">
        On 6 November 2024, we presented a sound composition created in Hamburg-Schnelsen as part of a literature festival in a church. By integrating field recordings and tape loops recorded on site, we designed an immersive listening experience specifically created for the spatial and acoustic atmosphere of the performance venue. In this context, we combine the warm, unamplified sounds of the church organ with audio tracks played back in a wide stereo field. The aim was to explore new acoustic spatial concepts through the interplay of different sound sources and to immerse the listener in a multi-layered soundscape.
        <span class="intro-arrow" id="dot-organ"><b>→</b></span>
        <br>
        <span class="credits">Photos: David Reineke</span>
      </Fragment>
    </WorkSection>

    <WorkSection
      id="work-4"
      year="2023"
      title="Skateland"
      type="Site-Specific Concert"
      background="carousel"
      carouselImages={['./pictures/Skateland1.webp', './pictures/Skateland2.webp', './pictures/Skateland3.webp']}
      previewClass="dot-preview"
      previewId="preview-skateland"
      previewImage="./pictures/Skateland_Plakat.webp"
      playerBodyId="bp-4"
      playerType="audio"
      audioSrc="./pictures/kommbaldwieder.mp3"
      playerLabel="PLAY AUDIO"
    >
      <Fragment slot="body">
        In 2023, we realized a site-specific concert at I Punkt Skateland, supported by the Claussen-Simon-Stiftung. The project focused on acoustic exploration as a means of creating immersive listening environments. Through the deliberate shaping of sonic space, layered sound structures emerged that invite alternative modes of spatial perception. The work engages with unconventional concert settings, integrating their specific conditions into the compositional process. In doing so, it examines established modes of listening and proposes a reconfiguration of spatial experience.
        <span class="intro-arrow" id="dot-skateland"><b>→</b></span>
        <span class="credits">Photos: David Reineke, Poster Design: Max Arff</span>
      </Fragment>
    </WorkSection>

    <WorkSection
      id="work-5"
      year="2022-"
      title="w/ Frank Koenen"
      type="Collaboration with Dance"
      background="carousel"
      carouselImages={['./pictures/Gabelstapler2.webp', './pictures/Gabelstapler1.webp', './pictures/Franktanzt(1).webp', './pictures/Franktanzt(2).webp']}
      previewClass="dot-preview"
      previewId="preview-frank"
      previewImage="./pictures/HermesTanzt.webp"
      playerBodyId="bp-5"
      playerType="audio"
      audioSrc="assets/audio/skateland.mp3"
      playerLabel="PLAY AUDIO"
    >
      <Fragment slot="body">
        In collaboration with Stockholm-based dancer and artist Frank Koenen, Hermes Hemmnis develop a shared performative practice rooted in an ongoing exchange between movement and sound. Each project begins with a concrete starting point – an object, a gesture, or an idea – proposed by Koenen, which serves as the foundation for a new composition. From this material, Hermes Hemmnis develop original music, to which Koenen in turn responds with a choreography. In performance, the music is always played live, creating a space in which sound and movement continuously inform and transform each other.
        <span class="intro-arrow" id="more-frank"><b>→</b></span>
        <span class="credits">Photo: Tim Albrecht</span>
      </Fragment>
    </WorkSection>

    <Releases />
    <About />
    <Dates />
    <ParticleSection />

  </main>
</Layout>
